{"title_page": "Nigel Dakin", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| term_start2         = \n| children            = \n| spouse              = Amanda Dakin\n| birth_place         = [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1964|2|28|df=yes}}\n| successor2          = \n| predecessor2        = \n| term_end2           = \n| office2             = \n| name                = Nigel John Dakin\n| successor           = \n| predecessor         = [[John_Freeman_(diplomat)|John Freeman]]\n| premier             = [[Sharlene Cartwright-Robinson]]\n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_end            = \n| term_start          = 15 July 2019\n| office              = Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands\n| order               = 15th\n| image               = Nigel Dakin photo 1.jpg\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Birmingham]] ([[B.A.]])<br/>[[Kingston University]] ([[M.B.A.]])\n}}\n\n'''Nigel John Dakin''' (born 28 February 1964) is a British Diplomat currently serving as [[Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands|Governor]] of the [[Turks and Caicos Islands|Turks and Caicos Islands.]] He assumed office on July 15, 2019 in a swearing in ceremony before the territory's [[House of Assembly (Turks and Caicos Islands)|House of Assembly]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/speeches/governor-dakins-inaugural-speech-15-july-2019|title=Governor Dakin's inaugural speech: 15 July 2019|website=GOV.UK|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>.\n\n== Personal life ==\nDakin was born on 28 February 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/OfficeOfPremierTCI/posts/2780199408765437|title=The Office Of The Premier - Turks and Caicos Islands|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Dakin was educated at the [[King Edward VI Five Ways School]], a co-educational state grammar school in [[Bartley Green]], [[Birmingham]], [[England]].  Dakin is married to Amanda Dakin, with whom he has two children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.tc/office-of-the-governor|title=You are being redirected...|website=www.gov.tc|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nDakin attended the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] between 1982 and 1983. Dakin attended the [[University of Birmingham]] between 1984 and 1987, where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in political science. He would later receive [[Masters in Business Administration]] from [[Kingston University]] in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/nigel-dakin-4a244214b|title=Nigel Dakin|last=Dakin|first=Nigel|date=|website=Linkedin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nDakin became an officer in the [[British Army]] in 1982, a position he retained until 1994 when he was promoted to serve as a Staff Officer in the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] advising the [[Secretary of State for Defence|Defence Secretary]] and [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] on matters relating to the [[Northern Ireland peace process|Irish Peace Process]].  \n\nIn 1996, Dakin accepted a position within the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] (FCO), During this time he served in various leadership roles relating to Nigeria, India, the United States, Pakistan, and Afghanistan. In 2013, Dukin served on the Executive Board of the FCO where he oversaw organisational transformation. In 2016 he became the Senior National Security and Foreign Policy Official to the [[UK Ambassador to the United States]], a position he left, along with his service in the UK diplomatic service, upon becoming Governor<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://menafn.com/1098539888/Foreign-and-Commonwealth-office-announces-new-governor-designate-for-Turks-and-Caicos-Islands|title=Foreign and Commonwealth office announces new governor designate for Turks and Caicos Islands|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. \n\nIn May of 2019, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office announced that Dakin would succeed outgoing Governor [[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]] as Governor of the Turks and Caicos<ref name=\":0\" />.  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dakin, Nigel}}\n[[Category:Governors of the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Kingston University]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VI Five Ways]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = \n| term_start2         = \n| children            = \n| spouse              = Amanda Dakin\n| birth_place         = [[United Kingdom]]\n| death_place         = \n| death_date          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1964|2|28|df=yes}}\n| successor2          = \n| predecessor2        = \n| term_end2           = \n| office2             = \n| name                = Nigel John Dakin\n| successor           = \n| predecessor         = [[John_Freeman_(diplomat)|John Freeman]]\n| premier             = [[Sharlene Cartwright-Robinson]]\n| monarch             = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| term_end            = \n| term_start          = 15 July 2019\n| office              = Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands\n| order               = 15th\n| image               = Nigel Dakin photo 1.jpg\n| honorific-suffix    = \n| alma_mater          = [[University of Birmingham]] ([[B.A.]])<br/>[[Kingston University]] ([[M.B.A.]])\n}}\n\n'''Nigel John Dakin''' (born 28 February 1964) is a British Diplomat currently serving as [[Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands|Governor]] of the [[Turks and Caicos Islands|Turks and Caicos Islands.]] He assumed office on July 15, 2019 in a swearing in ceremony before the territory's [[House of Assembly (Turks and Caicos Islands)|House of Assembly]].\n\n== Personal life ==\nDakin was born on 28 February 1964.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/OfficeOfPremierTCI/posts/2780199408765437|title=The Office Of The Premier - Turks and Caicos Islands|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Dakin was educated at the [[King Edward VI Five Ways School]], a co-educational state grammar school in [[Bartley Green]], [[Birmingham]], [[England]].  Dakin is married to Amanda Dakin, with whom he has two children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.tc/office-of-the-governor|title=You are being redirected...|website=www.gov.tc|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nDakin attended the [[Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]] between 1982 and 1983. Dakin attended the [[University of Birmingham]] between 1984 and 1987, where he received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in political science. He would later receive [[Masters in Business Administration]] from [[Kingston University]] in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/nigel-dakin-4a244214b|title=Nigel Dakin|last=Dakin|first=Nigel|date=|website=Linkedin|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nDakin became an officer in the [[British Army]] in 1982, a position he retained until 1994 when he was promoted to serve as a Staff Officer in the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] advising the [[Secretary of State for Defence|Defence Secretary]] and [[Chief of the Defence Staff (United Kingdom)|Chief of the Defence Staff]] on matters relating to the [[Northern Ireland peace process|Irish Peace Process]].  \n\nIn 1996, Dakin accepted a position within the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] (FCO), During this time he served in various leadership roles relating to Nigeria, India, the United States, Pakistan, and Afghanistan. In 2013, Dukin served on the Executive Board of the FCO where he oversaw organisational transformation. In 2016 he became the Senior National Security and Foreign Policy Official to the [[UK Ambassador to the United States]], a position he left, along with his service in the UK diplomatic service, upon becoming Governor<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://menafn.com/1098539888/Foreign-and-Commonwealth-office-announces-new-governor-designate-for-Turks-and-Caicos-Islands|title=Foreign and Commonwealth office announces new governor designate for Turks and Caicos Islands|last=MENAFN|website=menafn.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>. \n\nIn May of 2019, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office announced that Dakin would succeed outgoing Governor [[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]] as Governor of the Turks and Caicos<ref name=\":0\" />.  \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dakin, Nigel}}\n[[Category:Governors of the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century British diplomats]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Kingston University]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VI Five Ways]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military Academy Sandhurst]]\n", "name_user": "Lord of the East", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added sources.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nigel_Dakin"}
{"title_page": "2015 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 2015 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico\n| series             = [[2015 UCI World Tour]]\n| race_no            = 3\n| season_no          = 28\n| image              = Tirreno-Adriatico_2015_logo.jpg\n| date               = 11\u201317 March 2015\n| stages             = 7\n| distance           = 1004.3\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 25hr 11' 16\"\n| speed              = 39.9\n| first              = [[Nairo Quintana]]\n| first_team         = {{ct|MOV|2015}}\n| first_nat          = COL\n| first_color        = blue\n| second             = [[Bauke Mollema]]\n| second_team        = {{ct|TFR|2015}}\n| second_nat         = NED\n| third              = [[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]]\n| third_team         = {{ct|EQS|2015}}\n| third_nat          = COL\n| mountains          = [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]]\n| mountains_team     = {{ct|COL|2015}}\n| mountains_nat      = COL\n| mountains_color    = green\n| points             = [[Peter Sagan]]\n| points_team        = {{ct|TTS|2015}}\n| points_nat         = SVK\n| points_color       = red\n| youth              = Nairo Quintana\n| youth_team         = {{ct|MOV|2015}}\n| youth_nat          = COL\n| youth_color        = white\n| team               = {{ct|MOV|2015}}\n| previous           = [[2014 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|2014]]\n| next               = [[2016 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|2016]]\n|image_alt = Logo of the 2015 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico}}\n\nThe '''2015 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico''' was the 50th edition of the [[Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]] stage race. It took place from 11 to 17 March and was the third race of the [[2015 UCI World Tour]].<ref name=\"2015Schedule\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/uci-confirm-worldtour-calendar-2015 |title=UCI confirm WorldTour Calendar 2015 |accessdate=4 January 2015 |work=Cycling News}}</ref><ref name=\"Calendar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.uci.ch/road/calendar/detail#date=20150301&view=list&categ=257&country=0&classc=0 |title=2015 UCI Calendar |accessdate=4 January 2015 |work=UCI}}</ref> The race is one of the most important races in the early part of the cycling season and is used by riders preparing both for the [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tours]] and for the [[Classics (cycling)|classics]] season.\n\nThe route of the 2015 edition started and finished with [[individual time trial]]s, one of which was rescheduled from a team time trial shortly before the race began. In between, the race consisted of two stages suitable for [[Sprinter (cycling)|sprinters]], one for [[puncheur]]s and two for [[Climber (cycling)|climbers]]. The key stage of the race was stage 5, which involved a summit finish on [[Monte Terminillo]]. The defending champion from the [[2014 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|2014 edition]] was [[Alberto Contador]] ({{Ct|TTS|2015}}), who was expected to be challenged by three of the strongest stage racers in the world, [[Nairo Quintana]] ({{Ct|MOV|2015}}), [[Vincenzo Nibali]] ({{Ct|AST|2015}}) and [[Chris Froome]] ({{Ct|SKY|2015}}). Froome, however, pulled out shortly before the race.\n\nThe first individual time trial was won by [[Adriano Malori]] ({{Ct|MOV|2015|nolink = y}}), who kept the lead for the first two stages. [[Greg Van Avermaet]] ({{Ct|BMC|2015}}) and [[Wout Poels]] ({{Ct|SKY|2015|nolink = y}}) won the next two stages, each taking the race lead for one day. The queen stage to Monte Terminillo was won by Quintana, who took the overall lead and was able to defend it to the end of the race. [[Bauke Mollema]] ({{Ct|TFR|2015}}) finished second, 18 seconds behind Quintana, with [[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]] ({{Ct|EQS|2015}}) third.\n\n[[Peter Sagan]] ({{Ct|TTS|2015|nolink = y}}) won the points classification, after he won one stage and finished in the top ten on three others. The mountains classification was won by [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]] ({{Ct|COL|2015}}), while Nairo Quintana won the young riders classification as well as the overall race victory.\n\n== Teams ==\nAs Tirreno-Adriatico is a UCI World Tour event, all 17 [[List of 2015 UCI WorldTeams and riders|UCI WorldTeams]] were invited automatically and were obliged to send a squad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uci.ch/mm/Document/News/Rulesandregulation/16/82/39/2-ROA-20150619-E_English.pdf |title=UCI Cycling Regulations: Part 2: Road Races page 110 article 2.15.127 |work=[[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] |accessdate=1 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702030045/http://www.uci.ch/mm/Document/News/Rulesandregulation/16/82/39/2-ROA-20150619-E_English.pdf |archivedate=2 July 2015 }}</ref> Five [[UCI Professional Continental|Professional Continental]] teams received wildcard invitations.<ref>{{cite news | date=19 January 2015 | first1=Gregor | last1=Brown | url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/giro-ditalia/giro-ditalia-2015-wildcards-announced-ccc-colombia-153068 | title=Giro d\u2019Italia 2015 wildcards announced: CCC in, Colombia out | work=Cycling Weekly | accessdate=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{cyclingteamlist|title=WorldTeams|ALM|AST|BMC|OPQ|FDJ|IAM|LAM|LTB|MOV|OGE|GRS|GIA|KAT|BEL|SKY|TTS|TFR|year=2015}}\n{{cyclingteamlist|title=Wildcard teams|CSF|TNE|EUC|MTN|COL|year=2015}}\n\n== Pre-race favourites ==\nThe key stages on the general classification were expected to be the time trials and the summit finish.<ref name=cn-route /> The race was originally expected to be the first contest of the season between the four riders expected to contest the [[2015 Tour de France|Tour de France]]: the [[2014 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]] champion [[Alberto Contador]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}), the [[2013 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]] champion [[Vincenzo Nibali]] ({{ct|AST|2015}}), [[Nairo Quintana]] ({{ct|MOV|2015}}) and [[Chris Froome]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}). Shortly before the race, however, Froome withdrew on account of a chest infection (he had also withdrawn at the last minute in 2013).<ref>{{cite news|title=Froome withdraws from Tirreno-Adriatico|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/froome-withdraws-from-tirreno-adriatico|accessdate=17 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=10 March 2015}}</ref> Following Froome's withdrawal, Contador was seen as the main favourite for the race; he had demonstrated his form when he and Froome fought a close battle in the [[2015 Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda|Vuelta a Andaluc\u00eda]] a weeks earlier. Nibali, however, had not yet shown good form in the 2015 season, while Quintana had not raced for several weeks following a crash. Other riders considered to have a chance in the general classification included [[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]] ({{ct|EQS|2015}}), [[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]] ({{ct|KAT|2015}}), [[Dan Martin (cyclist)|Dan Martin]] ({{ct|GRS|2015}}) and [[Thibault Pinot]] ({{ct|FDJ|2015}}).<ref name=\"vn-preview\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrand|first1=Stephen|title=Tour contenders face off in Tirenno-Adriatico|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/preview|accessdate=17 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=10 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"cw-win\">{{cite news|last1=Puddicombe|first1=Stephen|title=Tirreno-Adriatico 2015: Who will win?|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/racing/tirreno-adriatico-2015-who-will-win-161428|accessdate=17 March 2015|work=Cycling Weekly|date=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs well as losing Froome from the general classification battle, the race also lost one of the riders expected to challenge for stage wins. [[Marcel Kittel]] ({{ct|GIA|2015}}) withdrew from the race with a virus. The principal sprinters left in the race were [[Mark Cavendish]] ({{ct|EQS|2015|nolink=yes}}), [[Elia Viviani]] ({{ct|SKY|2015|nolink=y}}), [[Tyler Farrar]] ({{ct|MTN|2015}}) and [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]] ({{ct|TNE|2015}}).<ref>{{cite news|title=Kittel out of Tirreno-Adriatico|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/kittel-out-of-tirreno-adriatico|accessdate=17 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=9 March 2015}}</ref> The race was also notable as the first time when [[Peter Sagan]] raced alongside Contador in the {{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=y}} team; Sagan was expected to feature both on the sprint stages and on the uphill finish on stage 3.<ref name=\"vn-preview\" />\n\n== Route ==\n\n[[File:Terminillo.JPG|thumb|[[Monte Terminillo]], the location of the summit finish on stage 5]]The Tirreno\u2013Adriatico is an important race in the early part of the road cycling season.<ref name=vn-preview /> It is the third [[UCI World Tour]] race of the year, running at the same time as [[2015 Paris\u2013Nice|Paris\u2013Nice]].<ref name=\"Calendar\"/> The two races are sometimes seen as being in competition for prestige and for the best riders. Tirreno\u2013Adriatico is an important test as part of riders' preparations both for the [[Grand Tour (cycling)|Grand Tour]]s and for the [[classics (cycling)|classics]] races, such as [[2015 Milan\u2013San Remo|Milan\u2013San Remo]].<ref name=\"cn-route\">{{cite news|title=2015 Tirreno-Adriatico route features Monte Terminillo|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/2015-tirreno-adriatico-route-features-monte-terminillo|accessdate=17 March 2015|work=[[Cyclingnews.com]]|date=18 December 2014}}</ref> The race generally takes the riders east across central Italy, from the [[Tyrrhenian Sea]] to the [[Adriatic Sea]]; the race is therefore sometimes known as the \"race of the two seas\" and the Italian names of the seas give the name Tirreno\u2013Adriatico.<ref name=\"vn-preview\">{{cite news | url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/froome-no-star-studded-tirreno-adriatico-wild-ride_362703 | title=Froome or no, star-studded Tirreno-Adriatico should be wild ride | work=Velonews | date=10 March 2015 | accessdate=17 March 2015 | author=Hood, Andrew}}</ref>\n\nThe race was originally intended to begin with a {{convert|22|km|1|adj=on}} [[team time trial]] around [[Lido di Camaiore]]. This was expected to be a difficult test and to result in significant gaps in the general classification.<ref name=\"cn-route\" /> Heavy wind and rain in the week before the race, however, forced the race organisers, [[RCS Sport]], to change this stage. Though the start and finish lines were unchanged, the stage was shortened, first to {{convert|5.7|km|1}}, then to {{convert|5.4|km|1}}; it was also changed to be an [[individual time trial]].<ref name=\"cw-s1\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/adriano-malori-wins-tirreno-adriatico-stage-one-time-trial-161837 | title=Adriano Malori wins Tirreno-Adriatico stage one time trial | work=[[Cycling Weekly]] | date=11 March 2015 | accessdate=17 March 2015 | author=Elton-Walters, Jack}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/bad-weather-forces-change-to-tirreno-adriatico-stage-one-161525 | title=Bad weather forces change to Tirreno-Adriatico stage one | work=Cycling Weekly | date=9 March 2015 | accessdate=17 March 2015 | author=Clarke, Stuart}}</ref> This was expected to result in smaller gaps; it was a particular blow to the {{ct|OGE|2015}} team, who had based most of their squad around the team time trial.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frattini|first1=Kirsten|title=Tirreno-Adriatico stage 1 change a blow to Orica-GreenEdge|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tirreno-adriatico-stage-1-change-a-blow-to-orica-greenedge|accessdate=17 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nStage 2 was a fairly flat stage, expected to suit the sprinters preparing for Milan\u2013San Remo. Stage 3 was also unlikely to change the general classification, though it included a steep uphill finish. The key stages, however, came on the weekend. Stage 4 was a difficult, mountainous stage with a downhill finish. The following day's route had a summit finish on the {{convert|16|km|0|abbr=on}} climb of [[Monte Terminillo]]. Stage 6 was another fairly flat stage and the race ended on the Adriatic coast with another individual time trial in [[San Benedetto del Tronto]].<ref name=\"cn-route\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Stage characteristics and winners\n|-\n!Stage\n!Date\n!Course\n!Distance\n!colspan=\"2\"|Type\n!Winner\n|-\n! 1\n|align=right| 11 March\n| [[Lido di Camaiore]]\n| <s>{{convert|22.7|km|1|abbr=on}}</s><br />{{convert|5.4|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| <s>[[Team time trial]]</s><br />[[Individual time trial]]\n| {{flagathlete|[[Adriano Malori]]|ITA}}\n|-\n! 2\n|align=right| 12 March\n| [[Camaiore]] to [[Cascina]]\n| {{convert|153|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[Image:Plainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Flat stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jens Debusschere]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! 3\n|align=right| 13 March\n| [[Cascina]] to [[Arezzo]]\n| {{convert|203|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[Image:Hillystage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Greg Van Avermaet]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! 4\n|align=right| 14 March\n| [[Arezzo|Indicatore (Arezzo)]] to [[Castelraimondo]]\n| {{convert|226|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[Image:Mediummountainstage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Medium-mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Wout Poels]]|NED}}\n|-\n! 5\n|align=right| 15 March\n| [[Esanatoglia]] to [[Monte Terminillo]]\n| {{convert|196.9|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[Image:Mountainstage.svg|22px]]\n| Mountain stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL}}\n|-\n! 6\n|align=right| 16 March\n| [[Rieti]] to [[Porto Sant'Elpidio]]\n| {{convert|210|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[Image:Hillystage.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| Hilly stage\n| {{flagathlete|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK}}\n|-\n! 7\n|align=right| 17 March\n| [[San Benedetto del Tronto]]\n| {{convert|10|km|1|abbr=on}}\n| [[File:Time Trial.svg|22px|alt=|link=]]\n| [[Individual time trial]]\n| {{flagathlete|[[Fabian Cancellara]]|SUI}}\n|}\n\n== Stages ==\n\n=== Stage 1 ===\n\n'''11 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Lido di Camaiore]], {{convert|5.4|km|1|abbr=on}} ([[Individual time trial|ITT]])'''\n\nStage 1 was originally intended to be a {{Convert|22.7|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} [[team time trial]], but bad weather (high wind and torrential rain) in the week leading up to the event made this impossible.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/tirreno-adriatico-team-time-trial-replaced-with-short-individual-test|title=Tirreno-Adriatico team time trial replaced with short individual test|author=Cycling News|work=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> The race organisers reduced the race to a {{Convert|5.7|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} [[individual time trial]]; on the day of the race, this was shortened by a further {{Convert|300|m|4 = -1}}. The course was based in the [[Lido di Camaiore]] holiday resort on the Tyrrhenian coast and was entirely flat. The out-and-back course meant that the riders had a tailwind on the first half of the course and a headwind on the second.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_1_Lido_di_Camaiore-profiles|title = Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Prologue|date = |accessdate = 17 March 2015|website = ProCyclingStats|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nThe early benchmark time was set by [[Daniel Oss]] ({{Ct|BMC|2015}}), who completed the course in 6' 08\". A good time was also set by [[Peter Sagan]] ({{Ct|TTS|2015}}), whose time was 6' 10\" and who was the best young rider in the prologue. Sagan did well to set such a good time, since he hit a pavement early in his ride and nearly fell. Oss kept the lead for a long time, but was eventually overtaken by [[Matthias Br\u00e4ndle]] ({{Ct|IAM|2015}}). Br\u00e4ndle, however, was immediately overtaken by [[Adriano Malori]] ({{Ct|MOV|2015}}), the Italian national time trial champion, who had two previous stage wins in Tirreno\u2013Adriatico time trials. Malori's time was 6' 04\". [[Maciej Bodnar]] ({{Ct|TTS|2015}}), [[Steve Cummings]] ({{Ct|MTN|2015}}) and [[Greg Van Avermaet]] ({{Ct|BMC|2015|nolink = y}}) all came close to Malori's time, but were unable to beat it. The principal favourite for the stage, former world time trial champion [[Fabian Cancellara]] ({{Ct|TFR|2015}}), finished one second behind Malori, who therefore won the stage, winning both the blue jersey of the overall leader of the race and the red jersey of the points classification leader.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-1/results|title = Tirreno-Adriatico: Malori wins opening individual time trial|last = Frattini|first = Kirsten|date = 12 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-1/live-report|title = Tirreno-Adriatico Stage 1: As It Happened|last = Ryan|first = Barry|date = 12 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]] ({{Ct|EQS|2015}}) was the fastest of the general classification contenders, finishing 19th on the stage, 10\" behind Malori. [[Vincenzo Nibali]] ({{Ct|AST|2015}}) was the first of the three major favourites for the race, one second behind Ur\u00e1n. [[Alberto Contador]] ({{Ct|TTS|2015|nolink = y}}) and [[Nairo Quintana]] ({{Ct|MOV|2015|nolink = yu}}) both lost time.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 1 Result and General Classification}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|1|Adriano Malori|2015|6' 04\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}{{cjersey|red|Points classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|2|Fabian Cancellara|2015|+ 1\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|3|Greg Van Avermaet|2015|+ 2\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|4|Maciej Bodnar|2015|+ 2\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|5|Matthias Br\u00e4ndle|2015|+ 2\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|6|Daniel Oss|2015|+ 4\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|7|Ram\u016bnas Navardauskas|2015|+ 5\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|8|Steve Cummings|2015|+ 6\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|9|Peter Sagan|2015|+ 6\"|{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|10|Johan Le Bon|2015|+ 8\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_1_Lido_di_Camaiore ProCyclingStats]}}\n\n=== Stage 2 ===\n\n'''12 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Camaiore]] to [[Cascina]], {{convert|153|km|1|abbr=on}}'''\n\nThe second stage of the race was a {{Convert|153|km|4 = 0|adj = on}} route from [[Camaiore]], the location of stage 1, to [[Cascina]]. The course started with one and a half laps of a circuit around Camaiore, including the only two categorised climbs of the day, before heading south-east towards the city of [[Lucca]]. After leaving Lucca, the course turned west, then headed north to enter [[Cascina]]. In Cascina, the riders completed two laps of a {{Convert|20.7|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} finishing circuit. Although the final circuit was flat, there were three roundabouts, a sharp turn and a bridge in the final {{Convert|5|km|1}}.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_2_Cascina-profiles|title = Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Stage 2|date = |accessdate = 17 March 2015|website = ProCyclingStats|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\nAn early breakaway was formed on the circuit around Camaiore. This was made up of seven riders: [[Edoardo Zardini (cyclist)|Edoardo Zardini]] ({{Ct|CSF|2015}}), [[Danilo Wyss]] ({{Ct|BMC|2015}}), [[Cristiano Salerno]] and [[Patrick Konrad]] ({{Ct|TNE|2015}}), [[Jorge Camilo Castiblanco]], [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]] (both {{Ct|COL|2015}}) and [[Martijn Keizer]] ({{Ct|BEL|2015}}). The breakaway built up a lead of over six minutes and took all the mountains classification points. Wyss won the first ahead of Quintero; Quintero beat Wyss on the second climb. Danilo Wyss went on to take the jersey for the leader of the mountains classification thanks to his better general classification standing after the stage. The breakaway was carefully controlled by the sprinters' teams \u2212 principally {{Ct|EQS|2015}} and {{Ct|TTS|2015}} \u2212 and with {{Convert|91|km|4 = 0}} remaining the breakaway had less than three minutes' lead. The gap was reduced to less than 90 seconds as the peloton entered the finishing circuit with {{Convert|41.4|km|4 = 1}} remaining.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-2/results|title = Tirreno-Adriatico: Debusschere wins stage 2 in Cascina|last = Westermeyer|first = Susan|date = 12 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Frasnes-lez-Anvaing - Tour de Wallonie, \u00e9tape 1, 26 juillet 2014, d\u00e9part (B100).JPG|thumb|upright|[[Jens Debusschere]] (photographed in 2014), the winner of stage 2]]\nAbout {{Convert|10|km|4 = 0}} later, Zardini attacked and was followed by Quintero and Salerno. These three riders continued alone; they had less than a minute's lead as they entered the final lap of the circuit with {{Convert|20.7|km|4 = 1}} remaining and were caught soon afterwards. There was a crash in the peloton {{Convert|11|km|4 = 0}} from the finish, which eliminated [[Matteo Pelucchi]] ({{Ct|LAM|2015}}) from contention, as well as causing some delay for {{Ct|OGE|2015}}'s general classification rider [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]].<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url = http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/road/jens-debusschere-wins-hectic-tirreno-stage-2-sprint_362997|title = Jens Debusschere wins hectic Tirreno stage 2 sprint|last = Powlison|first = Spencer|date = 12 March 2015|work = Velonews|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nGoing into the final kilometres of the race, several teams were competing at the front of the peloton. {{Ct|MTN|2015}}, {{Ct|TTS|2015|nolink = y}} and {{Ct|EQS|2015|nolink = y}} all tried to set up their sprinters, with [[Zden\u011bk \u0160tybar]] particularly prominent. {{Ct|MTN|2015|nolink = y}} led the group under the ''flamme rouge'' with {{Convert|1|km|4 = 1}} remaining, as [[Edvald Boasson Hagen]] attempted to lead out his teammate [[Tyler Farrar]]. In the final few hundred metres, however, there was a large crash. [[Mark Cavendish]] ({{Ct|EQS|2015|nolink = y}}) suddenly moved right, clashing wheels with [[Elia Viviani]] ({{Ct|SKY|2015}}). Cavendish was unable to continue sprinting, while Viviani was thrown from his bike while riding at over {{Convert|70|kph|4 = 0|abbr = on}}. Several other riders were brought down in the incident, including [[Sacha Modolo]] ({{Ct|LAM|2015}}) and [[Luka Mezgec]] ({{Ct|GIA|2015}}). This crash left a small group of 12 riders to contest the stage finish. [[Jens Debusschere]] ({{Ct|LTB|2015}}), riding in the colours of the Belgian national champion, outsprinted [[Peter Sagan]] ({{Ct|TTS|2015}}) on the line; [[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]({{Ct|TNE|2015|nolink = y}}) finished third.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/debusschere-savours-first-worldtour-win-at-tirreno-adriatico|title = Debusschere savours first WorldTour win at Tirreno-Adriatico|last = Farrand|first = Stephen|date = 12 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/elia-viviani-continues-at-tirreno-adriatico-despite-high-speed-crash|title = Elia Viviani continues at Tirreno-Adriatico despite high-speed crash|last = Farrand|first = Stephen|date = 12 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt was revealed after the stage that Cavendish's sudden movement had been caused by his chain falling off the big [[chainring]]. The loss of power caused him to swerve right and Viviani was unable to avoid him. Viviani suffered cuts and abrasions from the crash, though he avoided any broken bones and was able to complete the stage.<ref name=\":3\" /> {{Ct|EQS|2015|nolink = y}} were keen to investigate the incident, as [[Tom Boonen]] had suffered a similar problem in the [[2015 Tour of Qatar|Tour of Qatar]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/etixx-quickstep-to-investigate-cavendishs-dropped-chain-in-tirreno-adriatico|title = Etixx-QuickStep to investigate Cavendish's dropped chain in Tirreno-Adriatico|last = Farrand|first = Stephen|date = 12 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThanks to the time bonus he won for coming second, Sagan moved up into second place overall, on the same time as Malori. Debusschere, meanwhile, moved into the lead of the points classification.<ref name=\":1\" />\n{|\n| \n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 2 Result}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Jens Debusschere]]|BEL|{{ct|LTS|2015}}|3h 30' 18\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 0\"|{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL|{{ct|APP|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Alexander Porsev]]|RUS|{{ct|KAT|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Tyler Farrar]]|USA|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Magnus Cort Nielsen]]|DEN|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Roger Kluge]]|GER|{{ct|IAM|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Nicola Ruffoni]]|ITA|{{ct|CSF|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Zak Dempster]]|AUS|{{ct|APP|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Mark Renshaw]]|AUS|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_2_Cascina ProCyclingStats]}}\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=General Classification after Stage 2}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Adriano Malori]]|ITA|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|3h 36' 22\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 0\"|{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Fabian Cancellara]]|SUI|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 1\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Greg Van Avermaet]]|BEL|{{ct|BMC|2015}}|+ 2\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Matthias Br\u00e4ndle]]|AUT|{{ct|IAM|2015}}|+ 2\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Maciej Bodnar]]|POL|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 2\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Daniel Oss]]|ITA|{{ct|BMC|2015}}|+ 4\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Ram\u016bnas Navardauskas]]|LTU|{{ct|TCG|2015}}|+ 5\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 6\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Martijn Keizer]]|NED|{{ct|BEL|2015}}|+ 7\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_1_General_Classification ProCyclingStats]}}\n|}\n\n=== Stage 3 ===\n\n'''13 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Cascina]] to [[Arezzo]], {{convert|203|km|1|abbr=on}}'''\n\n[[File:Diksmuide - Ronde van Belgi\u00eb, etappe 3, individuele tijdrit, 30 mei 2014 (A044).JPG|thumb|[[Greg Van Avermaet]] (photographed in 2014), winner of stage 3|left]]\nStage 3 took the riders on a {{Convert|203|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} route from [[Cascina]] to [[Arezzo]]. The route was very similar to stage 3 of [[2014 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|the previous year's race]], with a long route east, including two categorised climbs, and a finishing circuit in Arezzo. In the 2015 edition, the riders did five laps of a {{Convert|15|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} circuit. The final {{Convert|1|km|4 = 1}} of the circuit was difficult: it was uphill, with one section of 11%, there was a narrow gate and one section of road was cobbled.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_3_Arezzo-profiles|title = Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Stage 3|date = |accessdate = 17 March 2015|website = ProCyclingStats|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2014_Stage_3_Arezzo-profiles|title = Tirreno-Adriatico 2014 \u2013 Stage 3|date = |accessdate = 17 March 2015|website = ProCyclingStats|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> On the previous year's stage, Peter Sagan had beaten [[Micha\u0142 Kwiatkowski]] ({{Ct|EQS|2015}}) in the sprint.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2014/stage-3/results|title = Sagan sprints to victory in Tirreno-Adriatico stage 3|last = |first = |date = 14 March 2014|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe early breakaway was formed by [[Nicola Boem]] ({{Ct|CSF|2015}}), [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]] ({{Ct|COL|2015}}), [[Chad Haga]] ({{Ct|GIA|2015}}), [[Danilo Wyss]] ({{Ct|BMC|2015}}) and [[Rick Flens]] ({{Ct|BEL|2015}}). Wyss, the leader of the mountains classification, won both mountain sprints, with Quintero behind him both times. With {{Convert|95|km|4 = 0}} left to race, the breakaway had a five-minute lead. Sagan's {{Ct|TTS|2015}} team, however, controlled the race carefully: [[Matteo Tosatto]] and [[Christopher Juul-Jensen]] both put in long efforts on the front of the peloton to bring the group back. The lead was less than a minute with {{Convert|30|km|4 = 0}} left to race and the breakaway split. {{Convert|18.5|km|4 = 1}} from the end, Boem and Haga were the last riders of the group to be caught.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-3/results|title = Tirreno-Adriatico: Van Avermaet wins stage 3|last = Frattini|first = Kirsten|date = 13 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n{{Ct|TTS|2015|nolink = y}} controlled the peloton in the following kilometres, with {{Ct|BMC|2015}}, {{Ct|SKY|2015}} and {{Ct|IAM|2015}} close behind. Sagan's teammates, however, were quickly running out and, with {{Convert|4|km|4 = 0}} remaining, he only had [[Maciej Bodnar]] left to support him. BMC, meanwhile, had several riders left to support [[Greg Van Avermaet]]. Van Avermaet was therefore perfectly positioned as the climb began and attacked towards the top. He won a small gap ahead of [[Zden\u011bk \u0160tybar]] ({{Ct|EQS|2015|nolink = y}}) and was able to hold on to his lead to take the stage victory. Sagan was the quickest in the final metres, but he had started too far back; although he was able to pass Stybar to finish second on the stage, he was unable to catch Van Avermaet. Sagan did, however, take the lead in the points classification. Van Avermaet took over the lead in the general classification thanks to the bonus seconds he won on the stage.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/sagan-refuses-to-be-ruffled-after-another-defeat-at-tirreno-adriatico|title = Sagan refuses to be ruffled after another defeat at Tirreno-Adriatico|last = Farrand|first = Stephen|date = 13 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/van-avermaets-tirreno-timing-just-right-classics-ahead_363248|title = Van Avermaet\u2019s Tirreno timing just right with classics ahead|last = Brown|first = Gregor|date = 13 March 2015|work = Velonews|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n{|\n| \n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 3 Result}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Greg Van Avermaet]]|BEL|{{ct|BMC|2015}}|4h 58' 17\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 0\"|{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Zden\u011bk \u0160tybar]]|CZE|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Filippo Pozzato]]|ITA|{{ct|LAM|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Fabian Cancellara]]|SUI|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Simon Geschke]]|GER|{{ct|TGA|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Paul Martens]]|GER|{{ct|BEL|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Andriy Hryvko]]|UKR|{{ct|AST|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Wout Poels]]|NED|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_3_Arezzo ProCyclingStats]}}\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=General Classification after Stage 3}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Greg Van Avermaet]]|BEL|{{ct|BMC|2015}}|8h 34' 31\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 2\"|{{cjersey|red|Points classification}}{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Adriano Malori]]|ITA|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 8\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Fabian Cancellara]]|SUI|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 9\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Matthias Br\u00e4ndle]]|AUT|{{ct|IAM|2015}}|+ 10\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Ram\u016bnas Navardauskas]]|LTU|{{ct|TCG|2015}}|+ 13\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Jonathan Castroviejo]]|ESP|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 16\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Edvald Boasson Hagen]]|NOR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 16\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Andriy Hryvko]]|UKR|{{ct|AST|2015}}|+ 17\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_3_General_Classification ProCyclingStats]}}\n|}\n\n=== Stage 4 ===\n\n'''14 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Arezzo|Indicatore (Arezzo)]] to [[Castelraimondo]], {{convert|226|km|1|abbr=on}}'''\n\nThe fourth stage of the race was the longest stage of the race at {{Convert|226|km|4 = 1}}. The route took the riders from [[Arezzo]] east, with intermediate sprints in [[Gubbio]] and [[Fabriano]] and two classified climbs. The riders then entered a {{Convert|11.5|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} finishing circuit around the town of [[Castelraimondo]]. The riders did two laps of the circuit, each of which included the climb of the Crispiero, a {{Convert|3.0|km|4 = 0|adj = on}} climb with an average gradient of over 9%. Following the climb, there was a technical {{Convert|6|km|4 = 0|adj = on}} descent into the stage finish.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_4_Castelraimondo-profiles|title = Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Stage 4|date = |accessdate = 17 March 2015|website = ProCyclingStats|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n[[File:Castelraimondo.jpg|thumb|[[Castelraimondo]], the finish of stage 4]]\nThe early breakaway was formed by two riders from {{Ct|OGE|2015}}, [[Mathew Hayman]] and [[Luke Durbridge]]. The two riders built up a lead of over seven minutes ahead of the main peloton, though it seemed that both riders had crashed at some point on the route, away from the view of the television cameras. Two separate chasing groups formed: one was made up of [[Nathan Haas]] ({{Ct|GRS|2015}}) and [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]] ({{Ct|COL|2015}}); the other was formed by [[Walter Pedraza]], [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Rubiano]] (both {{Ct|COL|2015}}) and [[Manuel Quinziato]] ({{Ct|BMC|2015}}). Neither of the chase groups was successful, however, and the lead pair stayed clear until Durbridge tired with {{Convert|21|km|4 = 0}} remaining. Hayman was caught soon afterwards.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-4/results|title = Tirreno-Adriatico: Poels wins in Castelraimondo|last = O'Shea|first = Sadhbh|date = 15 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn the first climb of the Crispiero, [[Giovanni Visconti (cyclist)|Giovanni Visconti]] ({{Ct|MOV|2015}}) attacked along with [[Michele Scarponi]] ({{Ct|AST|2015}}) and [[Juli\u00e1n Arredondo]] ({{Ct|TFR|2015}}). Visconti was the first to cross the summit, with [[Daniel Moreno]] ({{Ct|KAT|2015}}) catching the group on the descent. The riders were caught, however, on the flat section between the two climbs, with approximately {{Convert|10|km|4 = 0}} still to race. The peloton was led at this point by {{Ct|TTS|2015}}.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/skys-wout-poels-takes-tirreno-adriatico-stage-four-win-and-overall-lead-162234|title = Sky\u2019s Wout Poels takes Tirreno-Adriatico stage four win and overall lead|last = Puddicombe|first = Stephen|date = 14 March 2015|work = Cycling Weekly|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter the group was caught, {{Ct|ALM|2015}} came forwards in support of [[Domenico Pozzovivo]]. [[Alexis Vuillermoz]] led the peloton into the foot of the final climb, dropping Van Avermaet, the race leader, with about {{Convert|8|km|4 = 1}} left. [[Giampaolo Caruso]] ({{Ct|KAT|2015|nolink = t}}) was the next to attack. As he was approaching the summit and looking at the group behind, [[Wout Poels]] ({{Ct|SKY|2015}}) attacked and came past on Caruso's left.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/wouter-poels-takes-stage-4-overall-lead-2015-tirreno-adriatico_363332|title = Wouter Poels takes stage 4, overall lead at 2015 Tirreno-Adriatico|last = Hood|first = Andrew|date = 14 March 2015|work = Velonews|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPoels therefore entered the descent off the Crispiero alone, with several seconds lead over the main group. The main favourites for the general classification hesitated before taking up the chase, allowing Poels to build a lead. Eventually, Katusha attempted to chase him down, but Poels was able to make the most of the difficult descent and built a 20-second lead. Although this was reduced on the way to the finish, Poels held on to take the win, his first for {{Ct|SKY|2015|nolink = y}}. He also moved into the overall lead of the race, with a 17-second advantage over [[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]] ({{Ct|EQS|2015}}), who had won the sprint for second place in the group behind.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/poels-ready-to-fight-for-overall-victory-at-tirreno-adriatico|title = Poels ready to fight for overall victory at Tirreno-Adriatico|last = Farrand|first = Stephen|date = 14 March 2015|work = Cyclingnews.com|access-date = 17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nPoels, who was leading Sky in the absence of [[Chris Froome]], expressed hope after the stage that he would be able to defend his race lead on the summit finish the following day. In the other classifications, [[Thibaut Pinot]] ({{Ct|FDJ|2015}}) moved into the lead of the young riders competition, as he moved up to fourth place in the general classification. Carlos Quintero, having been part of the breakaway for the third day running, took enough mountain points on the stage to move into the lead of the mountains classification.<ref name=\":5\" />\n{|\n| \n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 4 Result}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Wout Poels]]|NED|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|5h 53' 38\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]]|ESP|{{ct|KAT|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Alexis Vuillermoz]]|FRA|{{ct|ALM|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Rinaldo Nocentini]]|ITA|{{ct|ALM|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Roman Kreuziger]]|CZE|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Giampaolo Caruso]]|ITA|{{ct|KAT|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Jurgen Van den Broeck]]|BEL|{{ct|LTS|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]|GBR|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 14\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_4_Castelraimondo ProCyclingStats]}}\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=General Classification after Stage 4}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Wout Poels]]|NED|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|14h 28' 18\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 17\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 26\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Thibaut Pinot]]|FRA|{{ct|FDJ|2015}}|+ 26\"|{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Roman Kreuziger]]|CZE|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 27\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Jonathan Castroviejo]]|ESP|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 28\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Bauke Mollema]]|NED|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 28\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 30\"|{{cjersey|red|Points classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Vincenzo Nibali]]|ITA|{{ct|AST|2015}}|+ 31\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Alberto Contador]]|ESP|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 32\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_4_General_Classification ProCyclingStats]}}\n|}\n\n=== Stage 5 ===\n\n'''15 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Esanatoglia]] to [[Monte Terminillo]], {{convert|199|km|1|abbr=on}}'''\n\nStage 5 was the [[queen stage]] of the 2015 Tirreno\u2212Adriatico and the only summit finish of the race. It took the riders on a {{Convert|199|km|4 = 1|adj = on}} course from [[Esanatoglia]]. The peloton first travelled south, crossing three significant climbs in the first {{Convert|72|km|4 = 0}}. The middle of the stage was flat, as the riders travelled southwest towards [[Terni]], but the final part of the stage was difficult. The route first passed through [[Rieti]], then turned east towards the summit finish at a ski station on [[Monte Terminillo]]. The final climb was {{Convert|16.1|km|4 = 1}} in length, with an average gradient of 7.3% and a total ascent of {{Convert|1175|m|4 = 0}}. The steepest sections were in the first part of the climb (one section had a gradient of 12%); the rest of the climb had a steady incline, except for the final few hundred metres of [[false flat]].{{sfn|RCS|2015|pp = 72\u201375}}<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_5_Terminillo-profiles | title=Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Stage 5 | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref> The stage took place in cold, difficult conditions with temperatures below {{convert|0|C}}. There were rumours before the stage that it would have to be cancelled, but these were refuted by the race organisers and the stage took place as planned.<ref name=\"cn-s5-report\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-5/results | title=Tirreno-Adriatico: Quintana wins stage 5 in Terminillo | work=Cyclingnews.com | date=16 March 2015 | accessdate=18 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:ToB 2013 - Nairo Quintana 04.jpg|left|thumb|upright|[[Nairo Quintana]] (photographed in 2013), winner of stage 5]]\nThe day's main breakaway was formed early on by [[Maxime Monfort]] ({{ct|LTB|2015}}), [[Michele Scarponi]], [[Andriy Hrivko]] (both {{ct|AST|2015}}), [[Alessandro De Marchi (cyclist)|Alessandro De Marchi]] ({{ct|BMC|2015}}), [[Matteo Montaguti]] ({{ct|ALM|2015}}), [[Paul Voss]] ({{ct|TNE|2015}}), [[Angel Vicioso]] ({{ct|KAT|2015}}) and [[Jesus Herrada]] ({{ct|MOV|2015}}). They built up a lead of over seven minutes after {{convert|60|km|0}} of racing. Monteguti won both mountain sprints early in the stage, with Scarponi second on both occasions. After the two climbs, the main peloton made an effort to reduce the breakaway's lead and the gap was reduced to two minutes at the base of the final climb of the day.<ref name=\"cn-s5-report\" />\n\nThe breakaway disintegrated on the final climb, with Scarponi, De Marchi and Monfort forming a lead group. In the peloton, [[Vasil Kiryienka]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}) and [[Ivan Basso]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}) were setting the pace. Scarponi pulled clear of De Marchi and Monfort to lead the race solo, as [[Roman Kreuziger]] and [[Alberto Contador]] ({{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=y}}) briefly pulled clear of the main pack. As the riders entered the final {{convert|5|km|0}}, snow began to fall. As Contador drifted back in the pack, [[Nairo Quintana]] ({{ct|MOV|2015|nolink=y}}) attacked and immediately broke clear of the pack. Contador tried to respond but was unable to take Quintana's wheel. Contador ended up in a group of about 15 riders chasing Quintana. [[Vincenzo Nibali]] ({{ct|AST|2015|nolink=yes}}) was dropped at this point, while Quintana quickly caught up to Scarponi.<ref name=\"cn-s5-report\" /><ref name=\"cw-s5\">{{cite news | url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/nairo-quintana-lays-early-season-marker-with-tirreno-adriatico-stage-win-162288 | title=Nairo Quintana lays early season marker with Tirreno-Adriatico stage win | work=Cycling Weekly | date=15 March 2015 | accessdate=18 March 2015 | author=Puddicombe, Stephen}}</ref>\n\nContador twice made attacks on the chasing group, but on both occasions was unable to break free, although the race leader, [[Wout Poels]] ({{ct|SKY|2015|nolink=y}}) was dropped. [[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]] ({{ct|EQS|2015}}) also made an unsuccessful attack. Finally, [[Bauke Mollema]] ({{ct|TFR|2015}}) put in a successful attack and dropped the group behind. Contador did most of the work in a group of five riders, including Ur\u00e1n, [[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]] ({{ct|KAT|2015}}), [[Thibaut Pinot]] ({{ct|FDJ|2015}}) and [[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]] ({{ct|OGE|2015}}). The group did not keep up a steady pace, however, and Quintana was able to reach the finish line with a lead of 41 seconds over Mollema and 55 seconds over Contador's group. Quintana therefore moved into the lead of the overall classification, 39 seconds ahead of Mollema and over a minute ahead of Contador. Poels, meanwhile, finished 16th on the stage, 1' 37\" behind Quintana, and dropped to tenth in the general classification.<ref name=\"cn-s5-report\" /><ref name=\"cw-s5\" />\n\nAfter the stage, several riders expressed displeasure with the extreme weather conditions. [[Fabian Cancellara]] ({{ct|TFR|2015|nolink=y}}) was prominent among them, as he had been in a dispute over hot weather at the [[2015 Tour of Oman]], with [[Filippo Pozzato]] ({{ct|LAM|2015}}) and [[Luca Paolini]] ({{ct|KAT|2015|nolink=y}}) expressing similar concerns. The conditions were particularly difficult for the riders in the [[gruppetto]], as the conditions they faced in the final kilometres were significantly worse than those faced by the race leaders. Cancellara and other riders called for an extreme-weather policy to govern racing in such conditions.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/fabian-cancellara-leads-calls-for-change-after-tirreno-blizzard-162350 | title=Fabian Cancellara leads calls for change after Tirreno blizzard | work=Cycling Weekly | date=16 March 2015 | accessdate=18 March 2015 | author=Clarke, Stuart}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/cancellara-speaks-out-for-the-peloton-after-snow-hits-tirreno-adriatico | title=Cancellara speaks out for the peloton after snow hits Tirreno-Adriatico | work=Cyclingnews.com | date=16 March 2015 | accessdate=18 March 2015 | author=Farrand, Stephen}}</ref>\n\n{|\n| \n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 5 Result}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|5h 26' 03\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Bauke Mollema]]|NED|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 41\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]]|ESP|{{ct|KAT|2015}}|+ 55\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 55\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Alberto Contador]]|ESP|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 55\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Thibaut Pinot]]|FRA|{{ct|FDJ|2015}}|+ 55\"|{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]|GBR|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 55\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Domenico Pozzovivo]]|ITA|{{ct|ALM|2015}}|+ 55\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Przemys\u0142aw Niemiec]]|POL|{{ct|LAM|2015}}|+ 1' 05\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Damiano Caruso]]|ITA|{{ct|BMC|2015}}|+ 1' 10\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_5_Terminillo ProCyclingStats]}}\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=General Classification after Stage 5}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|19h 54' 45\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Bauke Mollema]]|NED|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 39\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 48\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Thibaut Pinot]]|FRA|{{ct|FDJ|2015}}|+ 57\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Alberto Contador]]|ESP|{{ct|SAX|2015}}|+ 1' 03\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]|GBR|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 1' 04\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Domenico Pozzovivo]]|ITA|{{ct|ALM|2015}}|+ 1' 06\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]]|ESP|{{ct|KAT|2015}}|+ 1' 07\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 1' 12\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Wout Poels]]|NED|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|+ 1' 13\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_5_General_Classification ProCyclingStats]}}\n|}\n\n=== Stage 6 ===\n\n'''16 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[Rieti]] to [[Porto Sant'Elpidio]], {{convert|210|km|1|abbr=on}}'''\n\nThe sixth stage was the final road stage of the race. It took the riders from the city of [[Rieti]], at the foot of Monte Terminillo, northeast to finish on the Adriatic coast at [[Porto Sant'Elpidio]]. The stage was {{convert|210|km|1|abbr=on}} in length. The first part was a {{convert|181.2|km|adj=on}} route, which took the riders from the startline and across some medium mountains. The most difficult climb was at [[Montelparo]] and came {{convert|78.8|km|1}} from the finish line. Once the riders had reached Porto Sant'Elpidio, they entered a {{convert|14.4|km|1|adj=on}} finishing circuit. They first rode the final {{convert|8|km|1}} of the circuit and crossed the finish line; this was the final intermediate sprint of the day. They then completed two complete laps of the circuit. The final {{convert|1.6|km|1}} were entirely straight.{{sfn|RCS|2015|pp = 84\u201389}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Stage 6|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_6_Porto_Sant_Elpidio-profiles|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref> The stage took place in rainy conditions.<ref name=\"cn-s6-report\">{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Daniel|title=Tirreno-Adriatico: Sagan wins stage 6|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-6/results|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Peter Sagan, Tour of California 2012.jpg|thumb|[[Peter Sagan]] (photographed in 2012), winner of stage 6]]\nAn early breakaway formed at {{convert|15|km|0}}, involving [[Yukiya Arashiro]] ({{ct|EUC|2015}}), [[Stijn Devolder]] ({{ct|TFR|2015}}) and [[Alessandro Vanotti]] ({{ct|AST|2015}}). They were caught, however, on the climb at Montelparo, as {{ct|TTS|2015}} increased the pace in the peloton. Their team leader, [[Alberto Contador]], was one of the riders to set the pace on behalf of [[Peter Sagan]].<ref name=\"cn-s6-report\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Farrand|first1=Stephen|title=Sagan relieved rather than happy after his first win for Tinkoff-Saxo|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/sagan-relieved-rather-than-happy-after-his-first-win-for-tinkoff-saxo|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=16 March 2015}}</ref> On this climb, several of the race's main sprinters were unable to stay with the peloton. These included [[Mark Cavendish]] ({{ct|EQS|2015}}) and [[Luka Mezgec]] ({{ct|GIA|2015}}). The breakaway's advantage had been reduced to 1' 30\" and, soon after the summit of the climb, Devolvder sat up and was caught. Arashiro and Vanotti were caught soon after, with {{convert|50|km|0}} still to race.<ref name=\"cn-s6-report\" /><ref name=\"cw-s6\">{{cite news|last1=Wynn|first1=Nigel|title=Peter Sagan takes first victory of season in Tirreno-Adriatico|url=http://www.cyclingweekly.co.uk/news/latest-news/peter-sagan-takes-first-victory-of-season-in-tirreno-adriatico-162391|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Cycling Weekly|date=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nVanotti, however, attacked again and built a 40-second gap to the peloton, which was still led by {{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=yes}}. He was joined in the lead by [[Alexis Vuillermoz]] ({{ct|ALM|2015}}). The two riders rode together until there were {{convert|12|km}} remaining, when Vuillermoz attacked. {{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=yes}} were joined by {{ct|LTB|2015}} at the front of the pack and Vuillermoz was caught with {{convert|5|km}} remaining.<ref name=\"cn-s6-report\" /> Throughout this time, the group containing the main sprinters in the race had been unable to reduce the advantage, which was 4' with {{convert|30|km}} to race.<ref name=\"vn-s6\">{{cite news|title=Peter Sagan sprints to his first win of 2015 in Tirreno-Adriatico stage 6|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/road/peter-sagan-sprints-first-win-2015-tirreno-adriatico-stage-6_363522|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Velonews|date=16 March 2015}}</ref> Cavendish, along with his entire sprint train, pulled out of the race as they crossed the finish line for the first time in order to rest ahead of Milan\u2013San Remo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Etixx-Quickstep pulls Cavendish from cold, rainy Tirreno-Adriatico|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/news/etixx-quickstep-pulls-cavendish-from-cold-rainy-tirreno-adriatico|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAs the main peloton approached the finish line, it was led by {{ct|MTN|2015}}, who still had several riders in the main pack. {{ct|TTS|2015|nolink}} had no riders left to support Sagan. He therefore positioned himself behind the final {{ct|MTN|2015|nolink=y}} rider, [[Gerald Ciolek]], who was being led out by [[Edvald Boasson Hagen]]. Sagan passed Ciolek in the final {{convert|150|m}} win the stage. Ciolek finished second, with [[Jens Debusschere]] ({{ct|LTB|2015|nolink=yes}}) in third.<ref name=\"cn-s6-report\" /> This was Sagan's first win in nine months, when he won a stage of the [[2014 Tour de Suisse]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Gregor|title=After Tirreno-Adriatico stage 6 victory, is Sagan under pressure to win more?|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/after-tirreno-adriatico-stage-6-victory-is-sagan-under-pressure-to-win-more_363601|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Velonews|date=16 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nAll the general classification riders finished in the main group, so the standings were unchanged.<ref name=\"cn-s6-report\" />\n\n{|\n| \n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 6 Result}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|1|Peter Sagan|2015|5h 04' 13\"|{{cjersey|red|Points classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|2|Gerald Ciolek|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|3|Jens Debusschere|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|4|Magnus Cort Nielsen|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|5|Maximiliano Richeze|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|6|Edvald Boasson Hagen|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|7|Nikias Arndt|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Sam Bennett (cyclist)|Sam Bennett]]|IRL|{{ct|APP|2015}}|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|9|Ram\u016bnas Navardauskas|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|10|Alexey Lutsenko|2015|+ 0\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_6_Porto_Sant_Elpidio ProCyclingStats]}}\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=General Classification after Stage 6}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|1|Nairo Quintana|2015|24h 58' 58\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|2|Bauke Mollema|2015|+ 39\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|3|Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n|2015|+ 48\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|4|Thibaut Pinot|2015|+ 57\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|5|Alberto Contador|2015|+ 1' 03\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|6|Adam Yates|2015|+ 1' 04\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|7|Domenico Pozzovivo|2015|+ 1' 06\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|8|Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez|2015|+ 1' 07\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|9|Steve Cummings|2015|+ 1' 12\"}}\n{{cyclingresult-men|10|Wout Poels|2015|+ 1' 13\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_6_General_Classification ProCyclingStats]}}\n|}\n\n=== Stage 7 ===\n\n'''17 March 2015&nbsp;\u2013 [[San Benedetto del Tronto]] to San Benedetto del Tronto, {{convert|10.05|km|1|abbr=on}} ([[individual time trial|ITT]])'''\n\nThe seventh and final stage of the 2015 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico was another individual time trial. This stage was {{convert|10.05|km|1}} in length and took place entirely in the resort of [[San Benedetto del Tronto]] on the Adriatic seafront. The course was an out-and-back route. It first headed south, through an intermediate time check after {{convert|4.7|km}}, to a pair of 90-degree right hand turns halfway through the course. The course then headed north on almost entirely straight roads. The stage was flat throughout with no significant climbs.{{sfn|RCS|2015|p=96}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Tirreno-Adriatico 2015 \u2013 Stage 7|url=http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_7_San_Benedetto_del_Tronto-profiles|website=ProCyclingStats|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref>\n[[File:Fabian Cancellara SUI (8596897715).jpg|left|thumb|[[Fabian Cancellara]] (photographed in 2012), winner of stage 7]]\nThe early lead was taken by [[Maciej Bodnar]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}), who set a time of 11' 39\". His time was soon beaten, however, by [[Adriano Malori]] ({{ct|MOV|2015}}), the winner of stage 1 and the Italian national time trial champion. Malori's time was 11' 27\". Although [[Vasil Kiryienka]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}) came close, he was five seconds behind at the finish. [[Fabian Cancellara]] ({{ct|TFR|2015}}), who had come second to Malori on stage 1, set off as Malori was finishing. Cancellara was a second off Malori's time at the intermediate checkpoint, but he was five seconds quicker over the second part of the course and took the stage lead by four seconds. Cancellara's time would not be beaten by any of the remaining riders and he won the stage, with Malori in second and Kiryienka in third.<ref name=cn-s7-report>{{cite news|title=Tirreno-Adriatico: Quintana wins overall|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-7/results|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Cyclingnews.com|date=17 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Shea|first1=Sadhbh|title=Tirreno-Adriatico: Stage 7 As It Happened|url=http://www.cyclingnews.com/races/tirreno-adriatico-2015/stage-7/live-report|website=Cyclingnews.com|accessdate=19 March 2015|date=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThough the general classification riders did not have a chance of victory on the stage, there were still positions to be won and lost. The best time from the general classification riders was that of [[Alberto Contador]] ({{ct|TTS|2015}}), 31 seconds behind Cancellara, and he stayed in fifth place overall. [[Wout Poels]] ({{ct|SKY|2015}}), [[Steve Cummings]] ({{ct|MTN|2015}}) and [[Thibaut Pinot]] ({{ct|FDJ|2015}}) all put in good times, with Poels and Cummings moving up in the top ten and Pinot defending his fourth place ahead of Contador. [[Bauke Mollema]] ({{ct|TFR|2015|nolink=yes}}) also put in a strong ride, finishing ahead of [[Rigoberto Ur\u00e1n]] ({{ct|EQS|2015}}), who was seen as the better time triallist of the two. Mollema therefore defended his second place overall. He was not, however, able to catch the race leader. Quintana finished 55\" behind Cancellara in 55th place; he took the overall race victory ahead of Mollema by 18\".<ref name=cn-s7-report/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Powlison|first1=Spencer|title=Cancellara gets revenge in final Tirreno TT, Quintana confirms GC|url=http://velonews.competitor.com/2015/03/news/road/cancellara-gets-revenge-final-tirreno-tt-quintana-confirms-gc_363698|accessdate=19 March 2015|work=Velonews|date=17 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Sagan]] ({{ct|TTS|2015|nolink=yes}}), the leader of the points competition, only had to finish the stage within the time limit to win the classification. He came very close to failing: he was the slowest rider in the stage, finishing 2' 59\" behind Cancellara. It was, however, just enough to prevent his exclusion and to allow him the classification victory.<ref name=cn-s7-report/>\n{{clear}}\n{|\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=Stage 7 result}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Fabian Cancellara]]|SUI|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|11' 23\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Adriano Malori]]|ITA|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 4\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Vasil Kiryienka]]|BLR|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|+ 9\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Jonathan Castroviejo]]|ESP|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 12\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Maciej Bodnar]]|POL|{{ct|TTS|2015}}|+ 16\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Michael Hepburn]]|AUS|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 16\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Ramunas Navardauskas]]|LIT|{{ct|GRS|2015}}|+ 17\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 23\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Andrey Amador]]|CRC|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|+ 25\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Edvald Boasson Hagen]]|NOR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 26\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015_Stage_7_San_Benedetto_del_Tronto ProCyclingStats]}}\n||\n{{cyclingresult start|title=Final general classification}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|25h 11' 16\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Bauke Mollema]]|NED|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 18\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Rigoberto Uran]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 31\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Thibaut Pinot]]|FRA|{{ct|FDJ|2015}}|+ 35\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Alberto Contador]]|ESP|{{ct|TTS|2015}}|+ 39\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 40\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Wout Poels]]|NED|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|+ 56\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Domenico Pozzovivo]]|ITA|{{ct|ALM|2015}}|+ 59\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]|GBR|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 1' 09\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Roman Kreuziger]]|CZE|{{ct|TTS|2015}}|+ 1' 11\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015-result ProCyclingStats]}}\n|}\n\n== Classifications ==\n\nThere were four main classifications in the 2015 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico. The first and most important of these was the [[general classification]]. This was calculated by adding each cyclist's finishing times on each stage. Time bonuses were awarded to the first three finishers on road stages (stages 2\u20136): the stage winner won a ten-second bonus, with six and four seconds for the second and third riders respectively. Bonus seconds were also awarded to the first three riders at intermediate sprints (three seconds for the winner of the sprint, two seconds for the rider in second and one second for the rider in third. The leader of the general classification received a blue jersey and the winner of the classification was considered the overall winner of the race.{{sfn|RCS|2015|pp=124\u2013126}}\n\nThe second classification was the [[points classification]]. On each stage of the race, points were awarded to the top 10 riders. The winner won 12 points, with 10 for the second-placed rider, 8 for the third-placed rider and then one point fewer for each place down to tenth place. Points were also awarded to the top four riders at intermediate sprints, with five points for the winner of the sprint and three, two and one points for the riders in second, third and fourth places respectively. It was originally intended that points would not be awarded on stage 1 as it was a [[team time trial]]. After this was changed to an individual time trial, however, points were awarded on the stage, on the same scale as for an intermediate sprint. The winner of the points classification was awarded a red jersey.{{sfn|RCS|2015|p=124}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Classifica Punti di Tappa + Generale|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Speciali/TirrenoAdriatico/2014/it/download/T01_Classifica_Punti_Tappa_Generale.pdf|website=gazzetta.it|publisher=RCS|accessdate=19 March 2015|date=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe third classification was the [[mountains classification]]. On each of the road stages there were classified climbs on the route. The first riders to the top of the climb were awarded points in the mountains classification. For most of the climbs, the first four riders won points, with five, three, two and one points respectively. More points were awarded for the two most difficult climbs of the race. These were the summit finish to [[Monte Terminillo]] on stage 5 and the Poggio San Romualdo on stage 4. On these climbs, the winner won 15 points in the classification, with the next six riders also winning points. The rider with the most points was awarded the green jersey.{{sfn|RCS|2015|p=125}}\n\nThe final classification was the young riders classification. This was based on the general classification: the highest placed rider born after 1 January 1990 was the leader of the classification and was awarded a white jersey.{{sfn|RCS|2015|p=125}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size:smaller;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage\n|-\n! width=\"1%\"  | Stage\n! width=\"14%\" | Winner\n! style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" width=\"15%\"|General classification<br />{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}\n! style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" width=\"15%\"|Points classification<br />{{cjersey|red|Points classification}}\n! style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" width=\"15%\"|Mountains classification<br />{{cjersey|green|Mountains classification}}\n! style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" width=\"15%\"|Young rider classification<br />{{cjersey|white|Young rider classification}}\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Adriano Malori]]\n|style=\"background-color:lightblue;\" rowspan=2| [[Adriano Malori]]\n|style=\"background-color:salmon;\" | [[Adriano Malori]]\n|style=\"background-color:#EFEFEF;\"| ''not awarded''\n|style=\"background-color:white;\" rowspan=3| [[Peter Sagan]]\n\n|-\n| 2\n| [[Jens Debusschere]]\n|style=\"background-color:salmon;\" |[[Jens Debusschere]]\n|style=\"background-color:lightgreen;\" rowspan=2| [[Danilo Wyss]]\n|-\n| 3\n| [[Greg Van Avermaet]]\n|style=\"background-color:lightblue;\" | [[Greg Van Avermaet]]\n|style=\"background-color:salmon;\" rowspan=5| [[Peter Sagan]]\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Wout Poels]]\n|style=\"background-color:lightblue;\" |[[Wout Poels]]\n|style=\"background-color:lightgreen;\" rowspan=4| [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]]\n|style=\"background-color:white;\" |[[Thibaut Pinot]]\n|-\n| 5\n| [[Nairo Quintana]]\n|style=\"background-color:lightblue;\" rowspan=3|[[Nairo Quintana]]\n|style=\"background-color:white;\" rowspan=3|[[Nairo Quintana]]\n|-\n| 6\n|[[Peter Sagan]]\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Fabian Cancellara]]\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''Final'''\n!style=\"background-color:dodgerblue;\"| {{font color|white|Nairo Quintana|link=yes}}\n!style=\"background-color:red;\"| {{font color|white|Peter Sagan|link=yes}}\n!style=\"background-color:limegreen;\"| [[Carlos Quintero (cyclist)|Carlos Quintero]]\n!style=\"background-color:offwhite;\"| [[Nairo Quintana]]\n|}\n\n== Classification standings ==\n\n{{columns-start}}\n\n=== General classification ===\n\n{{cyclingresult start|title=Result of general classification}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|25h 11' 16\"|{{cjersey|blue|General classification}}{{cjersey|white|Youth classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Bauke Mollema]]|NED|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|+ 18\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Rigoberto Uran]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|+ 31\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Thibaut Pinot]]|FRA|{{ct|FDJ|2015}}|+ 35\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Alberto Contador]]|ESP|{{ct|TTS|2015}}|+ 39\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Steve Cummings]]|GBR|{{ct|MTN|2015}}|+ 40\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Wout Poels]]|NED|{{ct|SKY|2015}}|+ 56\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Domenico Pozzovivo]]|ITA|{{ct|ALM|2015}}|+ 59\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|9|[[Adam Yates (cyclist)|Adam Yates]]|GBR|{{ct|OGE|2015}}|+ 1' 09\"}}\n{{cyclingresult|10|[[Roman Kreuziger]]|CZE|{{ct|TTS|2015}}|+ 1' 11\"}}\n{{cyclingresult end|source=[http://www.procyclingstats.com/race/Tirreno_Adriatico_2015-result ProCyclingStats]}}\n\n{{column}}\n\n=== Points classification ===\n\n{{cyclingresult start|title=Result of points classification|points=yes}}\n{{cyclingresult|1|[[Peter Sagan]]|SVK|{{ct|TTS|2015}}|32|{{cjersey|red|Points classification}}}}\n{{cyclingresult|2|[[Fabian Cancellara]]|SUI|{{ct|TFR|2015}}|21}}\n{{cyclingresult|3|[[Jens Debusschere]]|BEL|{{ct|LTB|2015}}|20}}\n{{cyclingresult|4|[[Rigoberto Uran]]|COL|{{ct|EQS|2015}}|19}}\n{{cyclingresult|5|[[Greg Van Avermaet]]|BEL|{{ct|BMC|2015}}|18}}\n{{cyclingresult|6|[[Joaquim Rodr\u00edguez]]|ESP|{{ct|KAT|2015}}|16}}\n{{cyclingresult|7|[[Nairo Quintana]]|COL|{{ct|MOV|2015}}|15}}\n{{cyclingresult|8|[[Adriano Malori]]|ITA|