{"title_page": "Carole Baskin", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American animal rights activist}}\n{{use mdy dates |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carole Baskin\n| image              = Carole Baskin September 2019.png\n| alt                = Carole Baskin looks to her right side\n| caption            = Baskin in 2019\n| other_names        = {{hlist|Carole Murdock|Carole Lewis}}\n| birth_name         = Carole Stairs Jones\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|06|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Animal sanctuary]] executive|animal rights activist}}\n| known_for          = ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness<nowiki/>]]''\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Michael Murdock|1979|end=div.}}\n* {{marriage|[[Disappearance of Don Lewis|Don Lewis]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}\n* {{marriage|Howard Baskin|2004}}}}\n| children           = 1}}\n'''Carole Baskin''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Stairs Jones'''; born June 6, 1961) is an American [[animal rights]] activist and owner of [[Big Cat Rescue]], a non-profit animal sanctuary based near [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]]. She drew public attention for her role in the 2020 [[Netflix]] documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'' about private zoo operator [[Joe Exotic]]. The Netflix series follows both Baskin and Exotic, filming their ongoing and escalating feuds over exotic animals in private zoos. Following the series' release, Baskin has been targeted by [[Internet meme]]s related to the [[disappearance of Don Lewis]], her second husband.\n\n==Early life==\nBaskin was born on June 6, 1961 on the [[Lackland Air Force Base]] in [[Bexar County|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s1Gnw7SmYTQ|title=1961 06 06|author=Carole Baskin|date=February 26, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=YouTube}}</ref> She expressed an interest in saving cats when she was 9, but she decided against pursuing a career in veterinary medicine after she learned that veterinarians euthanize animals.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> She dropped out of high school and left home at 15 with a local roller rink employee.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|author=Robert Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=Intelligencer}}</ref> She then hitchhiked back and forth between Florida and [[Bangor, Maine]], sleeping under parked cars.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> She later purchased a [[Datsun]] truck and slept in the back with her pet cat.<ref name=\"Intel\"/>\n\nBaskin later returned to Florida and worked at a department store where she began a relationship with her boss Michael Murdock.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> She moved in with him when she was 17, got married, and had a daughter.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> To make money, she began breeding show cats;<ref name=\"Intel\"/> she also began rescuing bobcats and using llamas for a lawn trimming business.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\"/> She later became involved in the real estate business with her second husband [[Disappearance of Don Lewis|Don Lewis]].<ref name=\"DBeast\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBaskin and her then-husband Don Lewis founded [[Big Cat Rescue]], an [[animal sanctuary]] near [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] for [[big cat]]s, in 1992. Baskin is the current chief executive officer of Big Cat Rescue.<ref>{{Cite news |date=March 17, 2020 |first=Emma |last=Bullimore |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-03-17/netflix-doc-who-is-carole-baskin/|title=Who is Carole Baskin? Meet the real life activist from Netflix's Tiger King|website=Radio Times}}</ref><ref name= people>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Kim Kardashian Praises Tiger King \u2014 and Wonders if Carole Baskin Could Have Killed Her Husband|website=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012204/https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=2020-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117123404/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|archive-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Baskin has used social media such as [[Facebook]] and [[YouTube]] and her \"The Cat Chat\" podcast to promote her big cats activism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vengreso.com/blog/big-cat-rescue-carole-baskin|title=Big Cat Rescue's Carole Baskin|date=May 17, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Bernie Borges}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' have described Baskin as an [[animal rights]] activist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|title=What Happened After 'Tiger King'|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author1=Alan Yuhas|author2=Maria Cramer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402151248/https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tiger-king-carole-baskin-speaks-docuseries-1287488|title='Tiger King': Carole Baskin Speaks Out Against Netflix Documentary|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Josh Wigler|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331221343/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tiger-king-carole-baskin-speaks-docuseries-1287488|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Big Cat Rescue temporarily closed to the public due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Florida|coronavirus pandemic in Florida]].<ref name=\"esquire\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|title=Carole Baskin started a Nearly Lethal Feud in 'Tiger King.' Here's Where She Is Now.|first=Gabrielle|last=Bruney|date=March 23, 2020|website=Esquire|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325192139/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/ |first=Kayla |last=Cobb |title=Who Is Carole Baskin in 'Tiger King' and Where Is She Now?|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325130438/https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages===\n{{See also|Disappearance of Don Lewis}}\n[[File:Tiger at Big Cat Rescue.jpg|thumb|right|A tiger at Baskin's animal sanctuary [[Big Cat Rescue]] in 2012]]\nBaskin moved in with Michael Murdock when she was 17, her boss at the department store that she worked for.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> The couple married on April 7, 1979, but Baskin claims that she never loved him and only married him because her parents were disappointed that they had been living together outside of marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VE5jKxPp8tQ|title=1979 04 07|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=YouTube|author=Carole Baskin}}</ref> She became pregnant soon after,<ref name=\"Intel\"/> and daughter Jamie Veronica Murdock was born on July 16, 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E2TT7QhWVTM|title=1980 07 16|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020 |author=Carole Baskin|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Over time, Murdock became possessive and physically abusive.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin threw a potato at Murdock as he attempted to attack her when she was 19, and she ran out of their home barefoot,<ref name=\"Intel\"/> and she met Don Lewis on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa that night.<ref name=\"Intel\"/><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|author=Pam Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=The Daily Beast|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Sean Williams}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Baskin and ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his sex addiction,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=Oxygen|author=Gina Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin's Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|author=Douglas Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> timing the trips for whenever she was menstruating.<ref name=\"Bible\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a restraining order against her, claiming that she had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin's first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |first=Tilly |last=Pearce |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=Metro |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Baskin claims that he filed the restraining order because she would haul off some of his \"junk\" property whenever he visited Costa Rica.<ref name=\"Bible\"/> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis [[Disappearance of Don Lewis|disappeared]] in August 1997.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Lewis was declared legally dead in 2002.<ref name= people/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/ |first=Rosy |last=Cordero |date=March 24, 2020 |title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=EW.com}}</ref> A dispute ensued between Lewis' children and Baskin over the estate, which was mostly left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref>\n\nBaskin met Howard Baskin in November 2002 at a kick-off party for the newly formed No More Homeless Pets organization.<ref name=\"Howard\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin Weds Howard Baskin|website=Big Cat Rescue|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330155157/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/}}</ref> He joined Big Cat Rescue soon after as chairman of the advisory board.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> He proposed to her in November 2003.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> The couple married in November 2004.<ref name=\"Howard\"/>\n\n===Joe Exotic feud and ''Tiger King''===\nBaskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> She had been highly critical of Exotic and his [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] in [[Wynnewood, Oklahoma]].<ref name= wrap/> Exotic promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of her husband Don Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> In 2013, a court ordered him to pay her $1 million in damages, leading to his bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> In 2019, Exotic was charged with attempting to hire a contract murderer to kill her.<ref name=\"esquire\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|title=Zookeeper who killed tigers and tried to have rival murdered is sentenced to 22 years in prison|author=Karin Brulliard|website=Washington Post|date=January 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123131926/https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Universal Content Productions]] announced that they were adapting a Joe Exotic podcast for television, with [[Kate McKinnon]] portraying Baskin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/kate-mckinnon-star-tv-series-based-podcast-joe-exotic-1252455|title=Kate McKinnon to Star in TV Series Based on Podcast 'Joe Exotic'|date=November 5, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Lesley Goldberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109124926/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/kate-mckinnon-star-tv-series-based-podcast-joe-exotic-1252455|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Baskin was featured in ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a31898876/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now/|title=Carole Baskin From Netflix's 'Tiger King' Is Doing Just Fine, TYVM|first=Korin|last=Miller|date=March 23, 2020|website=Women's Health}}</ref> She later spoke out against the series, calling it \"salacious and sensational\", and she criticized directors [[Eric Goode]] and Rebecca Chaiklin.<ref name= wrap>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|title='Tiger King' Hitman Target Carole Baskin Shreds Netflix Docuseries: 'Salacious and Sensational'|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001140/https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She stated that the filmmakers lied about the nature of the series when they approached her about it. She claims that they told her that they were going to be making \"the big cat version of ''[[Blackfish (film)|Blackfish]]''\".<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Refuting Netflix Tiger King|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012206/https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After ''Tiger King'' was released, several Internet memes targeted Baskin and her speculated involvement in Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=KIRO 7|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n{{Animal rights|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baskin, Carole}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Activists from Florida]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Florida]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:People from Bexar County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Zoo directors]]\n[[Category:Zoo owners]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American animal rights activist}}\n{{use mdy dates |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Carole Baskin\n| image              = Carole Baskin September 2019.png\n| alt                = Carole Baskin looks to her right side\n| caption            = Baskin in 2019\n| other_names        = {{hlist|Carole Murdock|Carole Lewis}}\n| birth_name         = Carole Stairs Jones\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1961|06|06}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{hlist|[[Animal sanctuary]] executive|animal rights activist}}\n| known_for          = ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness<nowiki/>]]''\n| spouse             = {{Plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Michael Murdock|1979|end=div.}}\n* {{marriage|[[Disappearance of Don Lewis|Don Lewis]]|1991|2002|end={{abbr|legal d.|legal death}}}}\n* {{marriage|Howard Baskin|2004}}}}\n| children           = 1}}\n'''Carole Baskin''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Stairs Jones'''; born June 6, 1961) is an American [[animal rights]] activist and owner of [[Big Cat Rescue]], a non-profit animal sanctuary based near [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]], [[Florida]]. She drew public attention for her role in the 2020 [[Netflix]] documentary series ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'' about private zoo operator [[Joe Exotic]]. The Netflix series follows both Baskin and Exotic, filming their ongoing and escalating feuds over exotic animals in private zoos. Following the series' release, Baskin has been targeted by [[Internet meme]]s related to the [[disappearance of Don Lewis]], her second husband.\n\n==Early life==\nBaskin was born on June 6, 1961 on the [[Lackland Air Force Base]] in [[Bexar County|Bexar County]], [[Texas]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s1Gnw7SmYTQ|title=1961 06 06|author=Carole Baskin|date=February 26, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=YouTube}}</ref> She expressed an interest in saving cats when she was 9, but she decided against pursuing a career in veterinary medicine after she learned that veterinarians euthanize animals.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> She dropped out of high school and left home at 15 with a local roller rink employee.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\">{{Cite web|url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/joe-exotic-and-his-american-animals.html|title= Joe Exotic bred lions, tigers, and ligers at his roadside zoo. He was a modern Barnum who found an equally extraordinary nemesis.|author=Robert Moor|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=Intelligencer}}</ref> She then hitchhiked back and forth between Florida and [[Bangor, Maine]], sleeping under parked cars.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> She later purchased a [[Datsun]] truck and slept in the back with her pet cat.<ref name=\"Intel\"/>\n\nBaskin later returned to Florida and worked at a department store where she began a relationship with her boss Michael Murdock.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> She moved in with him when she was 17, got married, and had a daughter.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> To make money, she began breeding show cats;<ref name=\"Intel\"/> she also began rescuing bobcats and using llamas for a lawn trimming business.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/><ref name=\"Intel\"/> She later became involved in the real estate business with her second husband [[Disappearance of Don Lewis|Don Lewis]].<ref name=\"DBeast\"/>\n\n==Career==\nBaskin and her then-husband Don Lewis founded [[Big Cat Rescue]], an [[animal sanctuary]] near [[Tampa, Florida|Tampa]] for [[big cat]]s, in 1992. Baskin is the current chief executive officer of Big Cat Rescue.<ref>{{Cite news |date=March 17, 2020 |first=Emma |last=Bullimore |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/on-demand/2020-03-17/netflix-doc-who-is-carole-baskin/|title=Who is Carole Baskin? Meet the real life activist from Netflix's Tiger King|website=Radio Times}}</ref><ref name= people>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Kim Kardashian Praises Tiger King \u2014 and Wonders if Carole Baskin Could Have Killed Her Husband|website=PEOPLE.com|access-date=2020-03-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012204/https://people.com/tv/kim-kardashian-praises-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=2020-03-25|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200117123404/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin/|archive-date=January 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Baskin has used social media such as [[Facebook]] and [[YouTube]] and her \"The Cat Chat\" podcast to promote her big cats activism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vengreso.com/blog/big-cat-rescue-carole-baskin|title=Big Cat Rescue\u2019s Carole Baskin|date=May 17, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Bernie Borges}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' have described Baskin as an [[animal rights]] activist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|title=What Happened After 'Tiger King'|website=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|author1=Alan Yuhas|author2=Maria Cramer|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200402151248/https://www.nytimes.com/article/tiger-king-updates.html|archive-date=April 2, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tiger-king-carole-baskin-speaks-docuseries-1287488|title='Tiger King': Carole Baskin Speaks Out Against Netflix Documentary|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Josh Wigler|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331221343/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tiger-king-carole-baskin-speaks-docuseries-1287488|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Big Cat Rescue temporarily closed to the public due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Florida|coronavirus pandemic in Florida]].<ref name=\"esquire\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|title=Carole Baskin started a Nearly Lethal Feud in 'Tiger King.' Here\u2019s Where She Is Now.|first=Gabrielle|last=Bruney|date=March 23, 2020|website=Esquire|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325192139/https://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/a31903483/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now-alive-big-cat-rescue/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/ |first=Kayla |last=Cobb |title=Who Is Carole Baskin in \u2018Tiger King\u2019 and Where Is She Now?|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325130438/https://decider.com/2020/03/24/tiger-king-carole-baskin-where-is-she-now/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Marriages===\n{{See also|Disappearance of Don Lewis}}\n[[File:Tiger at Big Cat Rescue.jpg|thumb|right|A tiger at Baskin's animal sanctuary [[Big Cat Rescue]] in 2012]]\nBaskin moved in with Michael Murdock when she was 17, her boss at the department store that she worked for.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> The couple married on April 7, 1979, but Baskin claims that she never loved him and only married him because her parents were disappointed that they had been living together outside of marriage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VE5jKxPp8tQ|title=1979 04 07|date=March 21, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=YouTube|author=Carole Baskin}}</ref> She became pregnant soon after,<ref name=\"Intel\"/> and daughter Jamie Veronica Murdock was born on July 16, 1980.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E2TT7QhWVTM|title=1980 07 16|date=March 24, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020 |author=Carole Baskin|website=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> Over time, Murdock became possessive and physically abusive.<ref name=\"Intel\"/> Baskin threw a potato at Murdock as he attempted to attack her when she was 19, and she ran out of their home barefoot,<ref name=\"Intel\"/> and she met Don Lewis on Nebraska Avenue in Tampa that night.<ref name=\"Intel\"/><ref name=\"TheSecret\">{{Cite episode|title=The Secret|series=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|season=1|number=3|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> Baskin and Lewis engaged in an affair while both were still married.<ref name=\"TheSecret\"/> Baskin became one of Lewis' many girlfriends and she substantially grew his wealth by helping him buy and sell real estate in 1984.<ref name=\"People\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|title=Too Purrfect|date=December 7, 1998|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=[[People (magazine)|People]]|author=Pam Lambert|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329014604/https://people.com/archive/too-purrfect-vol-50-no-21/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple divorced each of their spouses and married in 1991.<ref name=\"DBeast\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/joe-exotic-built-a-wild-animal-kingdom-he-was-the-most-dangerous-predator-of-them-all|title=Joe Exotic Built a Wild Animal Kingdom. He Was the Most Dangerous Predator of Them All.|website=The Daily Beast|date=June 22, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|author=Sean Williams}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Baskin and ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]'', Lewis would take monthly flights to [[Costa Rica]] to deal with his sex addiction,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oxygen.com/crime-news/what-happened-to-carole-baskins-ex-husband-don-lewis-from-tiger-king|title=What Happened To Carole Baskin's Former Husband, Who Vanished In 1997?|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=Oxygen|author=Gina Tron}}</ref><ref name=\"Bible\">{{Cite web|url=https://brobible.com/culture/article/carole-baskin-boyfriend-restraining-order/|title=Carole Baskin\u2019s Boyfriend After Her Husband Disappeared Also Filed For A Chilling Restraining Order Against Her|author=Douglas Charles|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 1, 2020|website=BroBible}}</ref> timing the trips for whenever she was menstruating.<ref name=\"Bible\"/> In July 1997, Lewis filed a restraining order against her, claiming that she had threatened to kill him; the restraining order was rejected.<ref name=DonLewisMetro>{{Cite news |title=Tiger King: Who is Carole Baskin\u2019s first husband Jack 'Don' Lewis and when did he disappear? |first=Tilly |last=Pearce |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |website=Metro |date=March 19, 2020 |access-date=March 26, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326151850/https://metro.co.uk/2020/03/19/tiger-king-carole-baskins-first-husband-jack-donald-lewis-disappear-12423475/ |archive-date=March 26, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Baskin claims that he filed the restraining order because she would haul off some of his \"junk\" property whenever he visited Costa Rica.<ref name=\"Bible\"/> Lewis continued to live with Baskin afterwards.<ref name=\"WTSP\"/> Lewis told Baskin multiple times that he wanted a [[divorce]], but she did not think he was ever serious.<ref name=\"Charley\">{{cite web|url=http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|title=Jack Donald Lewis \u2013 The Charley Project|accessdate=April 2, 2020|date=September 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190927192040/http://charleyproject.org/case/jack-donald-lewis|archive-date=September 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Lewis [[Disappearance of Don Lewis|disappeared]] in August 1997.<ref name=\"WTSP\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/local/extras/disappearance-on-easy-street/67-396338130|title=Disappearance on Easy Street|website=WTSP|date=November 1, 2002|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> Lewis was declared legally dead in 2002.<ref name= people/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/tiger-king-carole-baskin-slams-netflix-documentary/ |first=Rosy |last=Cordero |date=March 24, 2020 |title='Tiger King' subject Carole Baskin slams Netflix doc, calls it 'salacious and sensational'|website=EW.com}}</ref> A dispute ensued between Lewis' children and Baskin over the estate, which was mostly left to Baskin.<ref name=DonLewisMetro /> The case is still open as of 2020.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/police-ask-for-new-leads-in-disappearance-of-don-lewis-husband-of-tiger-king-star-carole-baskin/|title=Police ask for new leads in disappearance of Don Lewis, husband of \"Tiger King\" star Carole Baskin|date=March 30, 2020|accessdate=March 31, 2020|website=[[CBS News]]}}</ref>\n\nBaskin met Howard Baskin in November 2002 at a kick-off party for the newly formed No More Homeless Pets organization.<ref name=\"Howard\">{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/|title=Carole Baskin Weds Howard Baskin|website=Big Cat Rescue|date=September 20, 2019|accessdate=March 31, 2020|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330155157/https://bigcatrescue.org/carole-baskin-weds-howard-baskin/}}</ref> He joined Big Cat Rescue soon after as chairman of the advisory board.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> He proposed to her in November 2003.<ref name=\"Howard\"/> The couple married in November 2004.<ref name=\"Howard\"/>\n\n===Joe Exotic feud and ''Tiger King''===\nBaskin has a long-running feud with private zoo owner [[Joe Exotic]].<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite episode|title=Not Your Average Joe|series=Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness|season=1|number=1|date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> She had been highly critical of Exotic and his [[Greater Wynnewood Exotic Animal Park]] in [[Wynnewood, Oklahoma]].<ref name= wrap/> Exotic promoted an unsubstantiated theory that Baskin was involved in the disappearance of her husband Don Lewis.<ref name=\"CBS\"/> In 2013, a court ordered him to pay her $1 million in damages, leading to his bankruptcy.<ref name=\"DBeast\"/> In 2019, Exotic was charged with attempting to hire a contract murderer to kill her.<ref name=\"esquire\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|title=Zookeeper who killed tigers and tried to have rival murdered is sentenced to 22 years in prison|author=Karin Brulliard|website=Washington Post|date=January 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123131926/https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2020/01/22/joe-exotic-zookeeper-sentencing/|archive-date=January 23, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, [[Universal Content Productions]] announced that they were adapting a Joe Exotic podcast for television, with [[Kate McKinnon]] portraying Baskin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/kate-mckinnon-star-tv-series-based-podcast-joe-exotic-1252455|title=Kate McKinnon to Star in TV Series Based on Podcast 'Joe Exotic'|date=November 5, 2019|accessdate=April 2, 2020|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|author=Lesley Goldberg|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200109124926/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/kate-mckinnon-star-tv-series-based-podcast-joe-exotic-1252455|archive-date=January 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2020, Baskin was featured in ''[[Tiger King: Murder, Mayhem and Madness]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a31898876/tiger-king-carole-baskin-now/|title=Carole Baskin From Netflix's 'Tiger King' Is Doing Just Fine, TYVM|first=Korin|last=Miller|date=March 23, 2020|website=Women's Health}}</ref> She later spoke out against the series, calling it \"salacious and sensational\", and she criticized directors [[Eric Goode]] and Rebecca Chaiklin.<ref name= wrap>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|title='Tiger King' Hitman Target Carole Baskin Shreds Netflix Docuseries: 'Salacious and Sensational'|date=March 24, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326001140/https://www.thewrap.com/tiger-king-carole-baskin-reacts-netflix-docuseries-joe-exotic/|archive-date=March 26, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> She stated that the filmmakers lied about the nature of the series when they approached her about it. She claims that they told her that they were going to be making \"the big cat version of ''[[Blackfish (film)|Blackfish]]''\".<ref name= wrap/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|title=Refuting Netflix Tiger King|date=March 22, 2020|access-date=March 25, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325012206/https://bigcatrescue.org/refuting-netflix-tiger-king/|archive-date=March 25, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> After ''Tiger King'' was released, several Internet memes targeted Baskin and her speculated involvement in Lewis' disappearance.<ref name=\"Kiro\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/trending/tiger-king-sheriff-seeking-leads-1997-disappearance-carole-baskins-2nd-husband/FCSINAFMEZD7TD6B64DBHL6GZA/|title='Tiger King': Sheriff seeking leads in 1997 disappearance of Carole Baskin's 2nd husband|website=KIRO 7|date=March 31, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Tiger King}}\n{{Animal rights|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baskin, Carole}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:Activists from Florida]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:American women chief executives]]\n[[Category:American women podcasters]]\n[[Category:Animal rights activists]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Florida]]\n[[Category:Internet memes introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:People from Bexar County, Texas]]\n[[Category:Zoo directors]]\n[[Category:Zoo owners]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ich", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:CURLY", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carole_Baskin"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]] amending from PC1 due to activity level |small=yes}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Europe}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 COVID-19 pandemic in Europe\n| map1            = Persons died due to coronavirus COVID-19 per capita in Europe.svg\n| legend1         = Cumulative number of deaths per million inhabitants from COVID-19 in Europe.<ref name=\"coronacount\"/><!-- Date and legend inside image -->\n| map2            = Coronavirus infected persons per capita in Europe.svg\n| legend2         = Confirmed cases of SARS-CoV-2 infected people in relation to the population of the country (cases per million inhabitants).<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>|link=Special:FilePath/Coronavirus_infected_persons_per_capita_in_Europe.svg \n| map3            = COVID-19 death per infected in Europe.svg\n| legend3         = Number of deaths per 100 confirmed COVID-19 infected inhabitants in Europe.<ref name=\"coronacount\"/><!-- Date and legend inside image -->\n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Europe]]\n| first_case      = [[Bordeaux]], [[France]]\n| arrival_date    = 21 January 2020\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]<ref name=\"20200130cdc\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/summary.html |title=2019 Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) Situation Summary |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126210549/https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-nCoV/summary.html |archive-date=26 January 2020 |access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases  = 91,942<ref name=\"coronacount\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/#countries |title=Coronavirus update (live) |date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live|website=www.worldometers.info|access-date=20 March 2020 }}</ref>\n| deaths          = 38,102<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 523,468<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n\n| suspected_cases = \n| territories     = 54<ref name=\"coronacount\"/>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=locations}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic data/Europe medical cases chart}}\nCountries in [[Europe]] have been affected by [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], the disease caused by the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|coronavirus]] responsible for the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2019\u201320 pandemic]] first recorded in [[Wuhan]], China.\n\nAs of 17 March 2020, all countries within Europe had a confirmed case of COVID-19, with [[Montenegro]]<ref>[https://twitter.com/MeGovernment/status/1239992049350447104 Two COVID-19 cases confirmed in Montenegro] ''twitter.com/MeGovernment'' accessed 17 March 2020</ref> the last European country to report at least one case. In 18 countries, at least one death has been reported.\n\nEurope was considered the active centre of COVID-19 according to the [[World Health Organization]] as of 13 March 2020.\n\nAs of 13 March 2020, cases by country across Europe had doubled over periods of typically 3 to 4 days, with some countries (mostly those at earlier stages of detection) showing doubling every 2 days.<ref>[https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus Max Roser, Hannah Ritchie and Esteban Ortiz-Ospina (2020) - \"Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19) \u2013 Research and Statistics\"] 13 March 2020, ''ourworldindata.org/coronavirus'', accessed 14 March 2020</ref>\n\n== Risk assessment for the pandemic in the EU/EEA and UK ==\nAs of 17 March 2020, there had been 2,740 reported deaths in the EU/EEA and UK from COVID-19<ref name=ECDC>{{cite web | url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/cases-2019-ncov-eueea |title = Situation update for the EU/EEA and the UK |accessdate= 15 March 2020 <!--08:00--> |website=www.ecdc.europa.eu |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> (25 March number: 10,049).\n\nOn 13 March 2020, the following COVID-19 related risks were assessed by the ECDC:<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.ecdc.europa.eu/en/current-risk-assessment-novel-coronavirus-situation | title=Daily risk assessment on COVID-19, 13 March 2020 |website=www.ecdc.europa.eu |date=13 March 2020 |accessdate= 13 March 2020}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Risk\n! Level\n|-\n| risk of severe disease associated with COVID-19 infection for people in the EU/EEA and UK: general population\n| moderate  \n|-\n| risk of severe disease associated with COVID-19 infection for people in the EU/EEA and UK: older adults and individuals with chronic underlying conditions\n| high\n|-\n| risk of milder disease, and the consequent impact on social and work-related activity,\n| high\n|-\n| risk of the occurrence of sub-national community transmission of COVID-19 in the EU/EEA and the UK\n| very high\n|-\n| risk of occurrence of widespread national community transmission of COVID-19 in the EU/EEA and the UK in the coming weeks \n| high\n|-\n| risk of healthcare system capacity being exceeded in the EU/EEA and the UK in the coming weeks\n| high\n|-\n|risk associated with transmission of COVID-19 in health and social institutions with large vulnerable populations \n| high\n|}\n\n== EU coordination ==\n{{see also|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics#European Union}}\nUnder the [[Subsidiarity#General principle of European Union law|European Union subsidiarity principle]], the European Union does not have the legal powers to impose health management policy or actions, such as quarantine measures or closing schools, on member states.<ref name=\"OKOpress_Szumowski_EU_claims\" />\n\nOn 28 February 2020, the EU opened a tender process for the purpose of purchasing COVID-19 related medical equipment. Twenty member states submitted requests for purchases. A second round procedure was opened on 17 March, for the purchase of gloves, goggles, face protectors, surgical masks and clothing. Poland was among the member states that applied for the second round tender procedure. The [[European Commission]] claimed that all the purchases were satisfied by offers. Commissioner [[Thierry Breton]] described the procedure as illustrating the power of EU coordination.<ref name=\"OKOpress_Szumowski_EU_claims\" /> On 19 March, the EU announced the creation of the [[rescEU]] strategic stockpile of medical equipment, to be financed at the level of 90% by the Commission, to deal with the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name=\"EUCommission_rescEU\" /> Former European Central Bank president [[Mario Draghi]] stated that member states should absorb coronavirus losses, rather than the private sector. He compared the impact of coronavirus to [[World War I]].<ref name=Euronews/>\n\nNine European countries\u2014Italy, France, Belgium, Greece, Portugal, Spain, Ireland, Slovenia and Luxembourg\u2014called for \"corona bonds\" (a type of [[eurobond (eurozone)|eurobond]]) in order to help their countries to recover from the epidemic, on 25 March. Their letter stated, \"The case for such a common instrument is strong, since we are all facing a symmetric external shock.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amaro |first1=Silvia |title=Nine European countries say it is time for 'corona bonds' as virus death toll rises |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/25/nine-eu-countries-say-its-time-for-corona-bonds-as-virus-deaths-rise.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=CNBC |date=25 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The EU can't agree on how to help Italy and Spain pay for coronavirus relief |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/27/economy/corona-bonds-eu/index.html |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=CNN}}</ref> Corona bonds were discussed on 26 March 2020 in a meeting between heads of government of EU member states, but Germany and the Netherlands ruled out issuing such bonds. The summit dragged out for three hours longer than expected due to the \"emotional\" reactions of the prime ministers of Spain and Italy.<ref>{{cite news |title=Virtual summit, real acrimony: EU leaders clash over 'corona bonds' |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/26/virtual-summit-real-acrimony-eu-leaders-clash-over-corona-bonds-151291 |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=POLITICO |language=en}}</ref><ref name=Euronews>{{cite news |title=What are 'corona bonds' and how can they help revive the EU's economy? |url=https://www.euronews.com/2020/03/26/what-are-corona-bonds-and-how-can-they-help-revive-the-eu-s-economy |accessdate=28 March 2020 |work=euronews |date=26 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[European Central Bank]] head [[Christine Lagarde]], who plans (separately) to issue more than 1 trillion euros in bonds in response to coronavirus, urged the EU to consider issuing corona bonds.<ref name=\"Euronews\" />\n\n== Statistics by country ==\n{{main|Template:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data}} \n{{more citations needed|section|date=March 2020}}\n\n[[File:COVID-19-Europe-selection-relative-deaths-log.svg|thumb|600px|Cumulative number of deaths per million inhabitants for a selection of European countries, over time. The legend is sorted in descending order of these values. Logarithmic vertical axis. Data source: [[ECDC]].<ref name=ECDC/>]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|+Summary table of confirmed cases in Europe (as of 1 April 2020)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bnonews.com/index.php/2020/02/the-latest-coronavirus-cases/|title=Tracking SARS-CoV-2: Map, data and timeline|last=News|first=B. N. O.|date=18 February 2020|website=BNO News|access-date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n!Country \n!Confirmed \n!Deaths\n!Recovered\n!Ref\n|-\n|{{Flagicon|ITA}} [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Italy|Italy]]\n|115,